Chlamydia pneumoniae is an important cause of community-acquired pneumonia in school-aged children: serological results of a prospective, population-based study. The aetiology of community-acquired pneumonia in childhood was studied in the total population of 8851 children in the area of 4 municipalities in eastern Finland. All cases of community-acquired pneumonia (n = 201) were registered during a surveillance period of 12 months between September 1, 1981 and August 31, 1982. The diagnosis of pneumonia was verified radiologically in all identified cases. The diagnosis of chlamydial infection was based on an antibody response measured by complement fixation (CF), by enzyme immunoassay (EIA IgG or IgM) or by microimmunofluorescence (MIF